The paper discusses the evaluation of opportunistic spectrum OFDMA networks, which falls under the category of networked systems and communication in computer science. Therefore, cs.NI (networking and internet architecture) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the impact of different spectrum sensing strategies on the throughput of the network, which falls under the category of information theory, making cs.IT (information theory) another likely sub-category. The paper also considers cochannel interference, which falls under the category of multimedia, making cs.MM (multimedia) a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the impact of different channel and subchannel allocation strategies, which falls under the category of security and cryptography, making cs.CR (security and cryptography) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper presents an analytical model that considers different primary and secondary user types, traffic, and priority levels, which falls under the category of systems and control, making cs.SY (systems and control) a possible sub-category.
